(21, 'Review: Marcus Ryan - Hablas Ingls?', '', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/21/content_21124033_1670688632972173_1703353794_n.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australian comedian, Marcus Ryan, combines culture and language in a show that explores the difficulties and highlights of solo travel. With the aid of a projector, Marcus begins the show in Spanish whilst donning the persona of an energetic Spaniard - a quirk that works very well. He then slips into his next character; a stereotype of a hippie-esque backpacker who claims to &quot;be on a journey&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout the next hour, Marcus continues to provide us with observational humour and wild tales from his adventures in Latin America. His spontaneity and ability to command the audience prove that he is a born-performer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The show comes to an end with a rather poignant message, that in order to be comfortable in life you have to accept and be happy with yourself. But then of course, in true Marcus Ryan style, the message is flipped on its head; revealing a hilarious punch line and leaving the audience in hysterics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;&iquest;Hablas Ingl&eacute;s?&#39; contains adult humour, character comedy&nbsp;and very relatable laughs. A must-see for anyone who enjoys witty banter and has travelled to another country at least once in their lives. You can catch &#39;&iquest;Hablas Ingl&eacute;s?&#39; at 5pm at The Three Sisters.</p>\r\n', 15, 1, '2017-08-26 10:41:58', '2017-08-26 11:28:07', 'review-marcus-ryan-hablas-ingles', 5, NULL, 0),
(22, 'Listen to \'Havslten\' - the new single from  Honeymilk', 'The Swedish lo-fi indie band have released a new single ahead of their upcoming album.', '<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img alt=\"Honeyblood, formerly a four-piece band from Stockholm.\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/22/content_012A0838.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 533px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Stockholm-based two-piece Honeymilk have just released a new single ahead of their upcoming sophomore album <em>I Want You To Be Very Happy</em>. The upbeat garage-pop &lsquo;Havsl&aring;ten&rsquo; - which roughly translates as &lsquo;Ocean Song&rsquo; has a catchy guitar hook, reminiscent of bands like Best Coast and Smith Westerns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Honeymilk, now recently a two-man band, is comprised of Marcus Admund and Nikki Nyberg. They said of their new single:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;When we wrote the song, just the first two guitar parts, and we were about to save this embryo on our cell phones it got this temporary name &ldquo;Havsl&aring;ten&rdquo; based on our totally diversified feelings for the big unknown ocean. This band&rsquo;s relation to the ocean is divided &ndash; Nikki loves it more than anything else; Marcus wants to stay as far away from it as possible. Might as well keep that title?!&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lyrics call for the better times of summer days, something which is all the more relatable now that winter in Scotland is upon us. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>I Want You To Be Very Happy</em> is out January 26th 2018 on Birds Records.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"no\" height=\"300\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/345179946&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;visual=true\" width=\"100%\"></iframe></p>\r\n', 17, 1, '2017-10-05 09:33:29', '2017-10-07 14:54:35', 'listen-to-havslaten-the-new-single-from-honeymilk', 1, NULL, 1),
(23, 'Interview with Donae\'O', 'Last week Rebecca Somer and Robbie James got to chat with him about his recent project Sixteen and growth as an artist. ', '<p><img alt=\"Prolific UK grime/hip hop artist Donae\'o\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/23/content_donaeo.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 450px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Best known for his song &ldquo;Party Animal&rdquo; and recent feature on Giggs&rsquo;s &ldquo;Lock Doh&rdquo;, Donae&rsquo;O has spent the past sixteen years establishing himself in the music industry. Just over a year ago, he finally signed to a major label, Island Records. He released his mixtape, <em>Sixteen</em>, in June to celebrate this shift in his career. Last week Rebecca Somer and Robbie James got to chat with him backstage at the O2 Academy Glasgow about his new project and growth as an artist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie James: &ldquo;You&rsquo;re supporting Dizzee Rascal on his Raskit Tour, which started last night in Liverpool. I had a few friends at the concert, so I saw it on Snapchat. It looked mad! How was the first night of the tour?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;It was tremendous. It was a good start. I didn&rsquo;t know what to expect. I had never really done concerts before. I&rsquo;ve only done one, which was mine. Never really been on tour, and Dizzee Rascal, he&rsquo;s one of, if not the, biggest in our scene. Sometimes you feel there&rsquo;s a bit of pressure, but yeah, it was cool.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca Somer: &ldquo;How did <em>Sixteen</em> come about?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I signed to Island [Records] in December, put out &#39;Black&#39; and &#39;Black&#39; did well. I was like, &lsquo;We need to put out a project now.&rsquo; They were like &lsquo;No, we think you need to build the buzz&rsquo;, and I was like &lsquo;Ok, cool, let me just make a mixtape, and put it out, so I thought let me just do <em>Sixteen</em>.&rsquo; It&rsquo;s a new experience. They let me hire out a studio, which I&rsquo;m not really used to doing. I&rsquo;m used to recording in my mum&rsquo;s house, in my bedroom in the corner. I thought &lsquo;let me just try something new&rsquo;, so I made it in three months. Usually, I make my albums in a year or year and a half. This was compressed, but it was a good experience. Now, I&rsquo;m ready. I can see now that when you&rsquo;re making records, sometimes you have to be in the moment, and that&rsquo;s what <em>Sixteen</em> taught me- that I can be in the moment and that I can make a project there and then.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"380\" src=\"https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/2yHiJQBtWhFCcMbIsTKLSh\" width=\"700\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie: &ldquo;I&#39;ve always wondered to what extent the songwriting process is a case of saying &#39;Right, this evening I&#39;m gonna go write a song&#39;, versus a more natural process that comes about while travelling?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I think it&rsquo;s a bit of both. I think you should be proactive in trying and then sometimes it may not come up unless you&rsquo;ve tried. Sometimes when you have a hit, you need to just go and make the album. You need to constantly feed your fans. You know what I&rsquo;m saying?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;What was your favourite track on <em>Sixteen</em>?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t really do the whole favourite track thing. All of my songs I like equally. That is why I&rsquo;ve never ever had a favourite record. The only thing I will say is my favourite to do is when I&rsquo;m performing, I like performing &lsquo;Move to Da Gyal Dem&rsquo; most because people respond to that the most. People dance to it the most. It&rsquo;s just a fun track to put on.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;How do you hope for people to respond to your music?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I hope they enjoy it really. That&rsquo;s it. I hope they enjoy it as much as I enjoy it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;Can you talk a little about how you&rsquo;ve evolved as a musician from your early days when you dropped your first singles &lsquo;Falling&rsquo; &amp; &lsquo;My Philosophy (Bounce)&rsquo; to today?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I think when I was coming in I didn&rsquo;t really know what I was doing. And now, I know a bit more. I still don&rsquo;t know what I&rsquo;m doing, but I know a bit more than I did then. I know that I will always make my way through. I remember how I was feeling back then. When you put out your first record, you don&rsquo;t know if you&rsquo;re ever going to do it again. Whereas now I don&rsquo;t feel like that. I always feel like I&rsquo;ll eventually make something, so I have way more confidence in my abilities than I did then.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;What&rsquo;s the greatest lesson you&rsquo;ve learned from being in the industry for so long?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;Always be able to stand on your own two. You&rsquo;re always going to need help, but it&rsquo;s better to be an individual than a team, meaning you should be confident in your own skills because when you join a team, it&rsquo;s your skills that you bring to the table, and you need to find a team that respects that and don&rsquo;t want you to be everyone else. You have to find your own way.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie: &ldquo;I read an interview of you in TRENCH recently, and it asked you to describe your career and journey through music with one word. You said &lsquo;independence.&rsquo; Where does that independence and self-sufficiency stem from?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;That was a necessity when I started because we didn&rsquo;t have platforms, and I wanted to make music, so I had to work it out for myself. I had a massive need and passion to make music and no platform to express that passion, so I had to create my own platform.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;What music or artists inspire you right now?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;Lotto Boyzz, Kojo Funds, J Hus, Skepta, Don-E. I&rsquo;m listening to a lot of Afro-wave. That&rsquo;s what they call it now.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Rebecca: &ldquo;What should we look forward to in your upcoming studio album?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know yet. I&rsquo;m still promoting <em>Sixteen</em>.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie: &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve recently released a new video for &lsquo;Let Me&rsquo; featuring Young T, Bugsey and Belly Squad. How&rsquo;s the reaction been for that? Have you been excited?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;Yeah, it&rsquo;s been really good to be honest. This is the third video we&rsquo;ve done from that mixtape. The response has been tremendous, so I&rsquo;m really happy about that.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/fkwdrQVd4fs\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie: &ldquo;You have got a few exciting things coming up. I saw that you&rsquo;ll be at BBC1 Radio Extra Live on the 11th of October in Manchester with J Hus, Bryson Tiller, Stefflon Don, etc. That&rsquo;s pretty exciting, right?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;Yes, very exciting. I&rsquo;m looking forward to it. They always support my music. It&rsquo;s great that I can give back.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Robbie: &ldquo;I must ask you one more thing before you go. Are you a fan of the video done by Big Shaq, the comedy creation of Michael Dapaah of &lsquo;Man&rsquo;s Not Hot&rsquo; on BBC Radio 1Xtra?&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Donae&rsquo;O: &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a massive fan of what he does. I think it&rsquo;s amazing how he created a T.V. series on Youtube off of these five characters, and Shaq was one of them, and like Shaq&rsquo;s journey from being a criminal to going the righteous path. Again, 1Xtra supported him in that journey because he&rsquo;s an actor, a comedy actor, but they supported it, and it&rsquo;s helped him get that deal. I think people should look at how he created his own way and created something that was entertaining. He went all the way with it and done it to the best of his ability. The fact that &#39;Man&rsquo;s Not Hot&#39; is charting. I hope he takes it into movies, and he&rsquo;s talented in that way. Clearly, he&rsquo;s ambitious that way and very focused, so I wish the best for him.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Listen to the full interview with Donae&rsquo;O&nbsp;on Friday&rsquo;s Music Team HUB Show at 3pm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 23, 1, '2017-10-10 16:16:33', '2017-10-11 16:28:07', 'interview-with-donae-o', 1, NULL, 1),
(24, 'Review: \'Contractions\' at Bedlam Theatre', '', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/29/content_22070434_1469105006511987_2004268036_o.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Reviewed by Hannah Wallis</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Come in. Sit down. How&rsquo;s things?&rsquo; And so it begins. A dark, absurdist and brutal comedy that descends into a disturbingly realistic prophecy of a corporate life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Emma, an employee at a big multinational, is bound to a contract whereby she must not leave any aspect of her private life undeclared in order to keep her job. This could be an ideal foundation for humour. The disparity over what Emma and Darren, her love interest, define as &lsquo;romantic&rsquo; is amusing, and the audience settles nicely into the comedy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But for the boss, the presence of a candle at the employee&rsquo;s &lsquo;romantic&rsquo; dinner is a matter of protocol, and needs to be resolved. The relentless probing has begun. The professional-personal boundary is obliterated. The boss tries an awkward human gesture, professing occasionally, &lsquo;oh, just small talk&rsquo;, but really, Emma&rsquo;s every utterance is being detailed and filed. The veneer of interest and care barely masks the obsessive and inhumane quest for answers; the term &lsquo;care&rsquo; is only familiar to her because of the company&rsquo;s &lsquo;duty of care&rsquo; pamphlet that she can produce at a flourish at any sign of emotion on Emma&rsquo;s part.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The set design of the simplistic office reflects the corporate environment. The nameless boss is on stage as the audience enters the auditorium, and does not leave until we do, fitting for a character with an obsessive commitment to her job and lack of a more human existence outside of the workplace. Even between scene changes, she doesn&rsquo;t leave her office den of manipulation and heartlessness, continuing to pace and do paperwork as a blue sterile light floods the stage. Perhaps the fact that the clock wasn&rsquo;t working was not intended, but it did serve to emphasise the obsessive, repetitive questions and heighten the intensity of the play.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thus the play swerves from comedy to sinister realism and it makes for uncomfortable viewing, which Mark Bartlett, author of the play, has mastered elsewhere, in his BBC drama, Doctor Foster. We&rsquo;re forced to keep watching, just as Emma is repeatedly summoned to the office, but we&rsquo;re begging for some kind of d&eacute;nouement, to put an end to this tortuous episode. But there&rsquo;s more, and as Emma brings a shoe box supposedly containing her dead son onto the stage, the audience is paralysed between laugher and distress in the climax to this piece of dark absurdist theatre. It&rsquo;s a relief to see the actresses step out of the office and smile, and to escape the nightmare we&rsquo;ve just endured with them.</p>\r\n', 5, 1, '2017-10-10 16:24:11', '2017-10-12 20:15:43', 'review-contractions-at-bedlam-theatre', 3, NULL, 1),
(25, 'Tim Hecker at Summerhall', 'The nuance of Tim Hecker\'s ambient music did not translate well in his performance at Summerhall.', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/24/content_Tim-Hecker-by-Emily-Berl-3.jpg\" style=\"width: 632px; height: 608px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Canadian ambient producer Tim Hecker has been <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/may/06/tim-hecker-review-st-john-at-hackney-london\">criticised in the past</a> for the lack of spectacle in his live shows and if fans anticipated a change of approach for his run of concerts this year- perhaps this time offering more visual appeal- &nbsp;last Wednesday&rsquo;s performance surely came as a disappointment. The decision to perform completely in darkness should ideally allow the artist&rsquo;s ego to retreat and the music to take over- but this artistic decision came across as arrogant and a cheap way of appearing profound.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Set in Summerhall&rsquo;s Dissection Room, Edinburgh&rsquo;s own dark ambient duo Super Inuit begin the evening. Their gravelly low bass is punctuated by beams of synth, samples of spoken-word and Fern Morris&rsquo; relaxed vocals (her voice occasionally reminiscent of Portishead&rsquo;s Beth Gibbons&rsquo;) &nbsp;which allows the audience to ease into the show. Ambient music is by no means easy-listening, and so Super Inuit serve as a suitable median between the uncomplicated music of everyday life and Tim Hecker&rsquo;s experimental synth-driven fuzz which we are soon to experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Hecker arrives onstage, the Dissection Room is plunged into near-total darkness- illuminated only by the blue emergency-exit sign. It remains this way for the rest of his 50 minute set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Armed to the teeth with synths and drum pads, Hecker doesn&rsquo;t play anything that is recognisably his. Since it has been well over a year following the release of his last album Love Streams, it would make sense if he has chosen to show us samples of some new projects. Even if this is the case, it appears as if he is making it up as he goes along. Rolling waves of feedback give way to dense droning bass which resonates in the floor and walls. Wailing peals of synth are interspersed with sporadic gargling sounds and long, drawn out thuds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One could argue that ambient music is equally about what you don&rsquo;t play as what you do- ambience is often formed from the absence of sound itself- and therefore, one might suggest that the decision to perform in a dark space could only serve to amplify the intricacies of the music. By removing the audience&rsquo;s reliance on seeing in order to be entertained, Hecker forces them to focus on his experimental ambient and drone music that engulfs the room. This vision-depravation however also allows the audience to focus on the uncomfortable feeling of standing for a prolonged period of time and the familiar glow of phone screens indicate that after a while, some become restless. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tim Hecker has said that he enjoys <a href=\"http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/tim-hecker-virgins\">&ldquo;inhabiting the tropes of religious music without that promise of angels at the end&rdquo;</a> and fans have in the past compared attending his performances to having a religious or spiritual experience. Hecker&rsquo;s performance did indeed remind me of being in church as a child- but not for the grandeur of the music. Instead I listened, wondering for how long I would be required to stand while internally hoping it would be over soon. I would hardly call that a religious experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 17, 1, '2017-10-10 20:31:11', '2017-10-10 20:33:07', 'tim-hecker-at-summerhall', 1, NULL, 1),
(26, 'James Yorkston, Kris Drever, and Dan Wilson at Summerhall', '', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/26/content_22368848_1704065562971630_174894110_o.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>James Yorkston, Kris Drever, and Dan Wilson of Withered Hand came on stage at the Dissection Room in Summerhall without much fanfare. After a short period of applause, the musicians immediately started playing on their three guitars while James Yorkston sang the tune. This first song set up an important expectation for the audience: this gig was not about any one of them. All three were on stage the entire time, alternating playing each other&rsquo;s songs. Using this strategy, Yorkston, Drever, and Wilson created an intimate and engaging show that felt like you were listening in on a jam session between three old friends. The most effective of the songs they played were those sung and performed by all three, replicating a traditional experience of folk music. It felt as if they were playing folk music the way it was meant to be played: informally, communally, and with a good sense of humor. Some of the sincerest and most genuine moments in the show were when they joked to each other about their kids and broke into laughter mid-song.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only downfall of their casual performance was that is was occasionally unpracticed to a fault. On one hand, if the show felt too polished, it would not have suited the acoustic music all three of the musicians play. However, they spent a few of the songs laughing throughout about mistakes being made on the guitar or on the mandolin. Although this did take away somewhat from the performance, the overall effect of watching the three talented and experienced musicians jam with each other for a couple of hours was one of familiarity, openness, and warmth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 136, 1, '2017-10-10 21:04:18', '2017-10-10 21:10:12', 'james-yorkston-kris-drever-and-dan-wilson-at-summerhall', 1, NULL, 0),
(27, 'Nate Collins, The Opera Comic and Dancing on Tables at Sneaky Petes', '', '<p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/28/content_dancing_on_tables.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 535px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A night put together by Scruff of the Neck and Fortune saw the Dunfermline band Dancing on Tables headlining at Sneaky Pete&rsquo;s. Trying to draw a crowd for the gig was a difficult feat with Scotland playing a crucial World Cup qualifier on the same night. However, by the end of the show there was indeed a healthy wee gathering.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first act of the night is a young solo artist named Nate Collins. Based in Edinburgh he has been working on several releases and his Soundcloud shows promise. His two latest releases &#39;Honey&rsquo; and &lsquo;Otherwise&rsquo; show song writing variety but it seems that during this performance the odds have been stacked against him. With several technical difficulties and slightly unfortunate out of time looping causing problems, he finishes the set with an abrupt ending to a Two Door Cinema Club cover. Although a slightly painful end to his set, I would definitely give him another chance as the talent and promise is quite obviously present.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shortly afterwards, the Opera Comic, a Leeds based, Noel Fielding look-alike band take the stage. Starting the set with a strange Willy Wonka cover they continue with what can only be described as pure and persistent indie. Their first single &lsquo;We Are the Freaks&rsquo; has that treble guitar sound so emblematic of the genre as well as the &lsquo;no one understands me&rsquo; message typical of indie anthems. Although slightly clich&eacute; it is definitely a well put-together and skilfully performed song. Their newest release &lsquo;A Time of Hope&rsquo; has more depth; ironically disregarding the lack of hope in the world at the moment. The performance is slick and they have full-on stage presence but it seems as if they offer nothing new or different. It will be interesting to see how they develop as a group.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now come the headliners of the night: Dancing on Tables are a band on the rise. Firmly established in the young Scottish alternative/indie scene they have been pleasing crowds with their soft, romantic songs all summer. Having played festivals all over the country including Kendal Calling and Solas, their set is a lot more organised and rehearsed than when I saw them last. The interesting use of two vocalists creates a dialogue in their music which is evident in the banter they have on stage. It is obvious that they are simply happy to be playing good music with their friends; and it&#39;s incredibly endearing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their debut EP <em>Don&rsquo;t Stop</em> features fuzzy guitar driven sound punctuated by intricate melody. For a four-track record, the variety in sound is amazing. The slight fuzz which permeates each track, works in their favour and shows the band&#39;s simple but lovely core. Their newest release &lsquo;Tracey&rsquo; in contrast, is clean cut and one for the dance floor and it goes down a treat during the show. A fantastic band full of promise, they will be releasing some new music at the start of November and I for one am excited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0cm 0cm 8pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 94, 1, '2017-10-12 20:03:38', '2017-10-12 20:09:56', 'nate-collins-the-opera-comic-and-dancing-on-tables-at-sneaky-petes', 1, NULL, 1),
(29, 'Listen to \"About This Thing\" by Young Franco and Scrufizzer', 'Listen to Young Franco\'s new single, \"About This Thing\"', '<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i1.sndcdn.com/avatars-000279297766-90mwio-t500x500.jpg\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 500px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">His first single in ten months, Australian DJ and producer Young Franco releases &ldquo;ABOUT THIS THING&rdquo;, an upbeat and bouncy tune showcasing Young Franco&rsquo;s distinctive pop house genre, with a bit of grime mixed in thanks to the U.K.&rsquo;s own Scrufizzer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">The track is certainly somewhat of an uncharted territory for the producer, yet &ldquo;About This Thing&rdquo; has every capacity to get listeners dancing along with the electronic bass and drum lines. While the tune has the potential to become repetitive and unvaried with each listen, it does provides an excellent gateway into</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">Young Franco&rsquo;s reserve of electronic tracks with his signature bass lines, ranging from pure house (&ldquo;Hurricane&rdquo;) to dance pop electronica (&ldquo;Drop Your Love&rdquo;) Young Franco has announced a live-streamed house party in honour of his new release on 20th October. &ldquo;About This Thing&rdquo; is out now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"no\" height=\"166\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/343351096&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true\" width=\"100%\"></iframe></p>\r\n', 59, 1, '2017-10-13 15:23:38', '2017-10-15 14:35:04', 'listen-to-about-this-thing-by-young-franco-and-scrufizzer', 1, NULL, 1),
(30, 'Tom Grennan at Saint Luke\'s', 'Illness fails to prevents Grennan\'s star quality shining through ', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/30/content_Tom-Grennan-_4_.jpg\" style=\"width: 710px; height: 500px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The recent trend in British pop music, growing since 2014, is for talented British solo artists to burst into public consciousness as guest vocalists on already established dance / drum&rsquo;n&rsquo;bass artist&rsquo;s singles. Think of Sam Smith (first hitting the charts with Disclosure on Latch), John Newman (similarly with Sigala on Feel the Love) and Anne-Marie (who appeared on four tracks on Rudimental&rsquo;s 2015 album We The Generation) to name just a few. Having appeared on Chase and Status&rsquo; 2016 single &lsquo;All Goes Wrong&rsquo;, it appears that Tom Grennan will soon be following this newly established route into the music mainstream. As any audience member at Tom Grennan&rsquo;s sold out show in Glasgow on the 7<sup>th</sup> October will tell you, for the Bedford born singer-songwriter it can&rsquo;t come soon enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite visibly struggling after being &ldquo;ill as a dog&rdquo; following a lengthy UK tour schedule, Grennan captivates the packed crowd of St Luke&rsquo;s Church this Saturday night with his unique vocals, charismatic stage presence and visible excitement for his own music. Kicking off the show with his latest single &lsquo;Royal Highness&rsquo; Tom clearly has the crowd on his side from the start. As the set continues, his sense of connection with the audience only increases as his honest, self-deprecating style comes to the fore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tempo of the set is controlled and varies impressively: from the up-beat festival-ready anthems (such as &lsquo;Lighting Matches&rsquo; and &lsquo;Giving It All&rsquo;) to the incredibly honest bluesy Jamie-T style crowd favourite &lsquo;Old Songs&rsquo;. The audience participates with him in change of pace throughout the performance. Whilst his stripped-back acoustic rendition of &lsquo;Sweet Hallelujah&rsquo; leaves the packed auditorium in an uncharacteristic quiet, his stunning vocals cause few to doubt Grennan&rsquo;s musical pedigree. The quiet doesn&rsquo;t last for long however. Typical of the entire set; Grennan&rsquo;s on stage energy instantly lifts the crowd for his hit &lsquo;Found What I&rsquo;ve Been Looking For&rsquo;. With the instantly recognisable introduction, from what is currently his most streamed single on Spotify (no doubt fuelled by its recent inclusion in the FIFA &rsquo;18 video game and as the theme music for Sky Sports&rsquo; Premier League Football coverage), the anthem is belted out by a packed audience</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While &lsquo;Found What I&rsquo;ve Been Looking For&rsquo; might be the most popular single of the evening, what is most impressive is&nbsp;Grennan&rsquo;s enthusiasm and confidence on stage while remaining incredibly honest and self-deprecating. More established performers may shy away from this, trying to create and maintain a public image. However, Grennan&rsquo;s unfiltered language, unique voice, quirky observations and admissions throughout the set (such as his confession that he was wearing a stinking shirt) mean that he really does stand out in the crowd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the old shirt, in the packed St Luke&rsquo;s Hall, the only lingering smell was one of a young man, full of ambition and just months away from smashing into the mainstream. If his performance in Glasgow on the 7<sup>th</sup> October is anything to go by, it&rsquo;s a collision that can&rsquo;t come too soon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Grennan&rsquo;s debut album Lighting Matches is scheduled for release on 9<sup>th</sup> March with a new tour beginning in Bristol on 15<sup>th</sup> March 2018. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Setlist:&nbsp;</b>Royal Highness, make &lsquo;em like you, Lighting Matches, Old Songs (acoustic), Lucky Ones, Aboard, Giving It All, Run in the Rain, Barbed Wire, All Goes Wrong, Praying, Sweet Hallelujah (acoustic), Found What I&rsquo;ve been Looking for, Something in the Water</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 118, 1, '2017-10-14 08:50:54', '2017-10-15 14:31:13', 'tom-grennan-at-saint-luke-s', 1, NULL, 1),
(31, 'Listen to Kari Faux\'s \"Gotta Know\"', '', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/32/content_6d0619876aec2cb364d4361e944602e5.742x742x1.jpg\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 400px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The talented alternative rap artist Kari Faux just released her new 7-song EP &ldquo;Primary&rdquo; this September. Faux has further refined her signature 90s inspired sound for her most recent project where she returned to her hometown of Little Rock, Arkansas to record, mix, and master the whole album herself for the first time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Gotta Know&rdquo;, a stand-out second track of the EP, was created in collaboration with the synth-pop producer, Jerry Paper. The mellow instrumentals and male vocal hook compliment Faux&rsquo;s punchy lines to create a satisfyingly chilled out sound. Faux has also released a cool Lo-Fi music video to accompany the song which you can watch on YouTube. In conjunction with the rest of the tracks on the EP, Faux reflects on her recent musical career and how her past has helped her stay true to herself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Primary&quot; is out now and be sure to check out &quot;Gotta Know&quot; below.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"no\" height=\"300\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/343089881&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true\" width=\"100%\"></iframe></p>\r\n', 90, 1, '2017-10-15 18:52:36', '2017-10-15 19:08:44', 'listen-to-kari-faux-s-gotta-know', 1, NULL, 1),
(32, 'Catching Up with Newton Faulkner', 'Laura Hendry chats to Newton Faulkner about his new album and upcoming tour.', '<p dir=\"ltr\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/36/content_102271.jpg\" style=\"width: 620px; height: 392px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>When you think about it, Newton Faulkner has been around for a fair old time. Ten years since he burst onto the music scene with the ever-sunny &lsquo;Dream Catch Me&rsquo; way back in 2007, the ginger-haired singer-songwriter has now shred his once famous dreadlocks and recently released his sixth studio album, <em>Hit the Ground Running</em>. Last week Laura Hendry got to chat to him about his new music and upcoming tour.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>You can catch Newton playing in Edinburgh at The Liquid Rooms on 28th October.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/tYkJSvXBMFk\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>So, whereabouts are you right now Newton? Are you currently in the UK?</b><br />\r\nI&rsquo;m currently in a taxi just going across London - I&rsquo;m going from North London to East London.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>You&rsquo;re playing a gig in Edinburgh in a few weeks time at The Liquid Rooms - have you played here before?&nbsp;</b><br />\r\nYeah, I&rsquo;ve played The Liquid Rooms a few times, actually, it&rsquo;s a great venue. This tour we&rsquo;re heading back to a lot of places that I&rsquo;ve either have done not that recently, or did years ago. I&rsquo;m heading back to a lot of places that I haven&rsquo;t been back to for a while.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>I&rsquo;m super excited to see that you&rsquo;re playing in Findhorn, which is a tiny coastal village not far where I&rsquo;m from in the North of Scotland! What is it that&rsquo;s driven you to play some of the more remote parts of the UK this time around?</b><br />\r\nI think they&rsquo;re generally better gigs! I&rsquo;ve played so many of the larger places so many times, it&rsquo;s nice to explore a bit more. There&rsquo;s always a great vibe to a big city gig, but I think you get a deeper connection with the crowd in the smaller venues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>I definitely agree with you on that one. Do you find that you get a bit more of a variation in the type of people that come to your gigs these days?&nbsp;</b><br />\r\nI don&rsquo;t think there could be any more variation in the crowds that come to my gigs! It&rsquo;s honestly the most diverse group of people that I&rsquo;ve ever come across. I recently had three generations of a family stay behind for a photo after a gig. The other thing that I hear quite a lot is that my music is often passed around families; I hear that kids have introduced their parents to it or vice versa and then everyone ends up coming to the gig. It&rsquo;s a beautiful thing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Your new album, <em>Hit the Ground Running</em> came out on 1st September 2017, which is 10 years since your first album was released. What&rsquo;s changed for you personally in that time, or in terms of your musical style?&nbsp;</b><br />\r\nWell, I just dropped my six-year-old son off at school, if that answers your question! But also, musically&hellip; well, the whole game&rsquo;s changed. The first album was big on MySpace. People were still talking about Bebo! And now it&rsquo;s obviously completely different. The way that the charts work is different, the way that people experience music has changed. And that&rsquo;s global. I&rsquo;ve never had more people ask me about vinyl than on the last European tour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Do you always release your material on vinyl in addition to the digital copies?</b><br />\r\nYeah. The latest record is independent, it&rsquo;s my own label. So I was definitely doing vinyl for this one! But when other people are in charge, they sometimes say &ldquo;Oh, we really don&rsquo;t need to do vinyl&rdquo;, and I&rsquo;m just like, &ldquo;Come on, man!&rdquo; But for this one we&rsquo;ve had some really good vinyl copies. In fact, I signed 500 of them over the last few days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Are there any particular gigs over the last ten years that have really stood out for you? Where&rsquo;s your favourite place to play?</b><br />\r\nI&rsquo;m just trying to think&hellip; I just really love playing, and I really don&rsquo;t care where. I almost don&rsquo;t even care to how many people! I&rsquo;ve had great gigs in tiny venues in other countries, countries I&rsquo;ve never been to before - places where I&rsquo;m just starting out - &nbsp;and there&rsquo;s a completely different vibe to that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>From your most recent album, who would you say that your greatest musical influences have been?&nbsp;</b><br />\r\nFor this one, it was much more soul influenced. Vocally, I was listening to stuff like Donny Hathaway and Chris Stapleton, quite serious vocalists, which is slightly different to usual because I&rsquo;m usually more of a guitar-nerd than a vocal-nerd. But then I think over the last few years I&rsquo;ve developed my voice a huge amount, partly through lessons and partly through really exploring it and pushing it on my own. I&rsquo;ve basically gained an octave and a half of range to play with. Most of this record I couldn&rsquo;t have sung a few years ago, like &lsquo;Hit the Ground&rsquo; - there&rsquo;s no way I could have got up there! And now the album lends itself to being played live so much more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>I&rsquo;m a big fan of your cover of &lsquo;Get Free&rsquo; by Major Lazer from the <em>Human Love</em> album. Do you have any other songs that you&rsquo;d like to cover in the future?&nbsp;</b><br />\r\nI think covers should be outside of your comfort zone, there&rsquo;s no point in covering something that you could have written anyway. Actually&hellip; I&rsquo;m not quite sure how this happened, but there was a certain character that at a gig of mine once, kind of Kenneth Williams-esque&hellip; for some reason he started rapping, and I started doing a bit of &lsquo;Ante Up&rsquo; by M.O.P, in the style of Kenneth Williams&hellip; it was completely random, but I kind of like that when an artist goes slightly off piste when they&rsquo;re live. Everyone knows you&rsquo;re just making it up as you go along, and as soon as they realise that, everyone&rsquo;s more engaged and more interested.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>You&rsquo;ve been pretty big on the festival circuit in recent years. Do you have any big ones that you like to play in particular?</b><br />\r\nGlastonbury will always be special to me, that was one of the first big festivals that I did. I actually played Bohemian Rhapsody in my pants one year&hellip; a weird way to spend an afternoon! A cold, cold experience. But gigwise, when it&rsquo;s just you on your own, you can react to anything, and every night I&rsquo;ve been playing songs that I didn&rsquo;t think I was going to play. It&rsquo;s a different level of freedom, it&rsquo;s so much fun. I do a huge amount of crowd participation. What I&rsquo;ve started doing recently is getting the crowd to do two different parts, then I do a part that harmonizes with half of one and the other half of the other, and every night I&rsquo;m astonished by what I hear coming back and how it sounds as a whole. It&rsquo;s just a really beautiful thing, it&rsquo;s a form of communication. I&rsquo;m very much from the school of thinking that I&rsquo;m there on stage to do whatever the crowd wants me to do, as opposed to the idea of &ldquo;I&rsquo;m gonna play and you&rsquo;re gonna listen&rdquo;. So if the crowd talks, that&rsquo;s my fault.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Amazing! Okay, one final qu</b><strong>estion from me.&nbsp;I&rsquo;m going to go a bit Desert Island Discs... If you were stranded on a desert island, what is your one luxury item that you&rsquo;d take with you, one book and one singular record?</strong><br />\r\nOkay&hellip; I think my luxury item would definitely have to be a guitar. As long as there&rsquo;s some coconuts on the island that I can use for percussion. Book-wise&hellip; I think I&rsquo;d take Jonathon Livingston&rsquo;s Seagull. I read that book once, if not twice, every year anyway. It&rsquo;s a beautiful book. Very short and easy to read but really beautiful - it reaffirms everything that you already know but which just occasionally might need reconfirming. And a single record&hellip; god, that&rsquo;s so hard! [long pause] I do think Joni Mitchell Blue covers a huge amount of ground. It&rsquo;s got some funkier tracks and then heartbreakingly beautiful things as well for when you need that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Thanks so much - looking forward to seeing you in Edinburgh in a few weeks time!</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 83, 1, '2017-10-18 16:05:23', '2017-10-18 21:24:42', 'catching-up-with-newton-faulkner', 1, NULL, 1),
(33, '\'Blanche and Butch\' at Summerhall', 'Reviewed by Sian Davies', '<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border: none; margin: 0cm 0cm 0.0001pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><i><img alt=\"\" src=\"/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/39/content_22556236_10208481973561392_1517157523_o.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 534px;\" /></i></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border: none; margin: 0cm 0cm 0.0001pt;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border: none; margin: 0cm 0cm 0.0001pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><i>By Sian Davies</i></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border: none; margin: 0cm 0cm 0.0001pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><i>With contributions from Cassandra Cassidy</i></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lsquo;Blanche and Butch&rsquo; opens with Blanche, played by Robert Softley Gale, making his way across the front of the stage on all fours. The sound of his limbs hitting the stage breaks the auditorium&rsquo;s silence. The audience is tense, and even as Blanche is christened with an extravagant feather headpiece laughs are withheld. The uncommon sight of a visibly disabled actor commanding the stage leads to clenched jaws and held breath, and proves exactly why this play has been created and should be seen. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; Set in the dressing room of a disabled, drag production of &lsquo;Whatever Happened to Baby Jane&rsquo;, the play&rsquo;s narrative develops through squabbles, proclamations about identity and shared moments of glory &ndash; including an Abba number. Though the premise &ndash; breaking the fourth wall to reveal backstage antics &ndash; is nothing new, the show&rsquo;s breaking down of social taboos should be commended.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"> &nbsp; &nbsp; The tension backstage builds to a breaking point when Bette forces Blanche to prove she cannot walk. This is depicted on stage, and perhaps unnecessarily. Drawn out, and with a foregone conclusion, instead of being gripped by the drama it left me waiting for it to reach the conclusion. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; T</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">he laughter is hesitant to begin with. However, as the show progresses, the audience begins to relax, and to realise that yes, the show is funny; and yes, these &lsquo;actually disabled&rsquo; actors are indeed capable of delivering unflinching jokes about &lsquo;spaz-fucks&rsquo; and facials. The atmosphere in the auditorium swells towards a triumphant and hearty applause at the plays conclusion.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">When the play isn&rsquo;t telling our prejudiced concept of disability to &lsquo;F*** Off&rsquo; (the concluding statement from Robert&rsquo;s searing monologue), it encourages the audience to engage in reflection &ndash; sometimes quite literally. At one point, whilst the characters inspect their appearance in on stage mirrors, glints of the audience are mixed with their reflections. Garry Robson&rsquo;s Butch delivers touching thoughts on his role as a father, and Kinny Gardner&rsquo;s Bette laments the passage of time. The audience, meanwhile, are faced with their own voyeuristic gaze reflected back at them, a powerful reminder of our own capacity to &lsquo;Other&rsquo; someone with just a look. It is a thought that stays with you long after the play&rsquo;s curtain. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Helvetica,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">&nbsp; It is also worth noting that with both a sign interpreter and a teleprompter for the hearing impaired, this story of intersectionality is accessible to all.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; text-align:justify; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; text-align:justify; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><em>For more information about Birds of Paradise Theatre Company, head to their website:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.boptheatre.co.uk/\">http://www.boptheatre.co.uk/</a></em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; text-align:justify; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"right\" class=\"Body\" style=\"border:none; text-align:right; margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 5, 1, '2017-10-19 15:05:26', '2017-10-30 16:57:22', 'blanche-and-butch-at-summerhall', 3, NULL, 1);
